I see some interesting lines:
- `17597: PHINode *NewPhi = Builder.CreatePHI(VecTy, PH->getNumIncomingValues());`
- `17600: // Adjust insertion point once all PHI's have been generated.`
- `23441: static Instruction *getReductionInstr(const DominatorTree *DT, PHINode *P, ...)`
- `24283: // Try to vectorize reductions that use PHINodes.`
- `24284: if (PHINode *P = dyn_cast<PHINode>(It)) {`

The code around line 24283 seems to be the entry point for vectorizing reductions involving PHI nodes. This is in `SLPVectorizerPass::runImpl`. It iterates over instructions and if it finds a PHI, it tries to vectorize it as a reduction.

The function `vectorizeRootInstruction` (line 23645) is also mentioned, which seems to be called for reductions.

Let's look at `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree`. This is where the actual vectorization of a tree of instructions happens. The logic for PHI nodes is special.

Around line 17589, in `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree`, there's a `case Instruction::PHI:`. This seems to be where the new vector PHI node is created.
```cpp
// llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:17589
    case Instruction::PHI: {
      // ...
      PHINode *NewPhi = Builder.CreatePHI(VecTy, PH->getNumIncomingValues());
      // ...
      // Add the incoming values to the new PHI node.
      for (unsigned I = 0, E = PH->getNumIncomingValues(); I != E; ++I) {
        BasicBlock *IBB = PH->getIncomingBlock(I);
        // ...
        Value *Inc = getVectorValue(TE, I);
        NewPhi->addIncoming(Inc, IBB);
      }
```
The `getVectorValue` function is what recursively generates the vector operands. This is where things can go wrong. `getVectorValue` for a given `TreeEntry` and operand index `I` will generate the vector code for that operand.

The reproducer has a loop. The PHI nodes have two incoming values, one from the preheader (`%bb`) and one from the loop body itself (`%bb1`).
When `getVectorValue` is called for the incoming value from `%bb`, it should generate code that is placed in `%bb`. When called for the value from `%bb1`, it should generate code within `%bb1`.

The dominance error suggests that an instruction that should be in `%bb1` is being used by an instruction in `%bb`, or an instruction that is supposed to be in the loop pre-header is using a value defined inside the loop.

The function `getVectorValue` is defined around line 18726. It takes a `TreeEntry` and an `EdgeIdx`. The `EdgeIdx` corresponds to the operand index, which for a PHI node is the incoming value index.

```cpp
// llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
Value *BoUpSLP::getVectorValue(TreeEntry *TE, unsigned EdgeIdx) {
  // ...
  // Generate the vectorized code.
  Instruction *User = TE->getMainOp();
  // ...
  if (PHINode *PH = dyn_cast<PHINode>(User)) {
    // For PHI nodes, we need to add the incoming value to the new PHI
    // node. We can't do it here because the new PHI node may not be created
    // yet. We save the incoming value and the block and add them to the new
    // PHI node later.
    Value *V = PH->getIncomingValue(EdgeIdx);
    // ...
    return getOperand(V);
  }
  // ...
}
```
This seems to be a simplified view. The actual logic is more complex. The real `getVectorValue` is probably `BoUpSLP::getVectorValue(ArrayRef<Value *> VL, unsigned EdgeIdx)`.

Let's look at `BoUpSLP::vectorizeRoot`. This is the main entry point for vectorizing a single root.
It calls `buildTree` which constructs the `VectorizableTree`. Then it calls `vectorizeTree`.

The problem is likely in how the initial value for the recurrence is handled.
In the reproducer, `%phi = phi i32 [ %or4, %bb1 ], [ 0, %bb ]`.
`%or4` is the recurrent value. `0` is the initial value.
When vectorizing, the SLP vectorizer will create a vector PHI.
It will have two incoming values.
One from `%bb1`, which will be the vectorized version of `%or4` (and its lane-partners).
One from `%bb`, which will be a vector of the initial values. Here, `<0, 0>`.

The problem might be that when trying to compute the vector for `%or4`, it somehow uses a value that is only defined in `%bb1` to construct the initial vector in `%bb`.

